# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heapsort-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] A sorting algorithm falls into the **adaptive sort** family if it takes advantage of existing order in its input.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] It benefits from the presortedness in the input sequence – or a limited amount of disorder for various definitions of measures of disorder – and sorts faster.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Adaptive sorting is usually performed by modifying existing sorting algorithms.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Comparison-based sorting algorithms have traditionally dealt with achieving an optimal bound of *O*(*n* log *n*) when dealing with time complexity.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Adaptive sort takes advantage of the existing order of the input to try to achieve better times, so that the time taken by the algorithm to sort is a smoothly growing function of the size of the sequence *and* the disorder in the sequence.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] In other words, the more presorted the input is, the faster it should be sorted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] This is an attractive feature for a sorting algorithm because sequences that nearly sorted are common in practice.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Thus, the performance of existing sorting algorithms can be improved by taking into account the existing order in the input.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] A classic example of an adaptive sorting algorithm is insertion sort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] In this sorting algorithm, the input is scanned from left to right, repeatedly finding the position of the current item, and inserting it into an array of previously sorted items.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] The performance of this algorithm can be described in terms of the number of inversions in the input, and then ⁠ $T(n)$ ⁠ will be roughly equal to ⁠ $I(A)+(n-1)$ ⁠, where ⁠ $I(A)$ ⁠ is the number of inversions.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Using this measure of presortedness – being relative to the number of inversions – insertion sort takes less time to sort the closer the array of data is to being sorted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/adaptive-sort] Other examples of adaptive sorting algorithms are adaptive heap sort, adaptive merge sort, patience sort, Shellsort, smoothsort, splaysort, Timsort, and Cartesian tree sorting.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] A **binary heap** is a heap data structure that takes the form of a binary tree.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Binary heaps are a common way of implementing priority queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Williams in 1964 as a data structure for implementing heapsort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Heaps where the parent key is greater than or equal to (≥) the child keys are called *max-heaps*; those where it is less than or equal to (≤) are called *min-heaps*.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Binary heaps are also commonly employed in the heapsort sorting algorithm, which is an in-place algorithm as binary heaps can be implemented as an implicit data structure, storing keys in an array and using their relative positions within that array to represent child–parent relationships.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Both the insert and remove operations modify the heap to preserve the shape property first, by adding or removing from the end of the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Then the heap property is restored by traversing up or down the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Compare the added element with its parent; if they are in the correct order, stop.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] If not, swap the element with its parent and return to the previous step.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Steps 2 and 3, which restore the heap property by comparing and possibly swapping a node with its parent, are called *the up-heap* operation (also known as *bubble-up*, *percolate-up*, *sift-up*, *trickle-up*, *swim-up*, *heapify-up*, *cascade-up*, or *fix-up*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The number of operations required depends only on the number of levels the new element must rise to satisfy the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Thus, the insertion operation has a worst-case time complexity of O(log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] For a random heap, and for repeated insertions, the insertion operation has an average-case complexity of O(1).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The following animation depicts an example of binary heap insertion.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] It begins by inserting 15 into the heap at the left-most empty entry on the next available row.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] However, the heap property is violated since 15 > 8, so we need to swap the 15 and the 8.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Even after this swap, the heap property is still violated since 15 > 11, so we need to swap again.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The heap property is now satisfied, so the resulting binary tree is a valid max-heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Compare the new root with its children; if they are in the correct order, stop.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] If not, swap the element with one of its children and return to the previous step.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] So, if we have the same max-heap as before, we remove the 11 and replace it with the 4.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Now the heap property is violated since 8 is greater than 4.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] In this case, swapping the two elements, 4 and 8, is enough to restore the heap property and we need not swap elements further.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The downward-moving node is swapped with the *larger* of its children in a max-heap (in a min-heap it would be swapped with its smaller child), until it satisfies the heap property in its new position.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This functionality is achieved by the **Max-Heapify** function as defined below in pseudocode for an array-backed heap *A* of length *length*(*A*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] For the above algorithm to correctly re-heapify the array, no nodes besides the node at index *i* and its two direct children can violate the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The down-heap operation (without the preceding swap) can also be used to modify the value of the root, even when an element is not being deleted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] In the worst case, the new root has to be swapped with its child on each level until it reaches the bottom level of the heap, meaning that the delete operation has a time complexity relative to the height of the tree, or O(log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Inserting an element then extracting from the heap can be done more efficiently than simply calling the insert and extract functions defined above, which would involve both an `upheap` and `downheap` operation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Python provides such a function for insertion then extraction called "heappushpop", which is paraphrased below.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The heap array is assumed to have its first element at index 1.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Finding an arbitrary element takes O(n) time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This can be easily proved by considering that the heap is not sorted so we need to look through the whole tree to find the target element.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Swap this element with the last element.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Down-heapify or up-heapify to restore the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] In a max-heap (min-heap), up-heapify is only required when the new key of element i is greater (smaller) than the previous one because only the heap-property of the parent element might be violated.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Assuming that the heap-property was valid between element i and its children before the element swap, it can't be violated by a now larger (smaller) key value.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] When the new key is less (greater) than the previous one then only a down-heapify is required because the heap-property might only be violated in the child elements.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The decrease key operation replaces the value of a node with a given value with a lower value, and the increase key operation does the same but with a higher value.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This involves finding the node with the given value, changing the value, and then down-heapifying or up-heapifying to restore the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Building a heap from an array of n input elements can be done by starting with an empty heap, then successively inserting each element.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This approach, called Williams' method after the inventor of binary heaps, is easily seen to run in *O*(*n* log *n*) time: it performs n insertions at *O*(log *n*) cost each.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] However, Williams' method is suboptimal.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] A faster method (due to Floyd) starts by arbitrarily putting the elements on a binary tree, respecting the shape property (the tree could be represented by an array, see below).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Then starting from the lowest level and moving upwards, sift the root of each subtree downward as in the deletion algorithm until the heap property is restored.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This process takes $O(h)$ operations (swaps) per node.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] In this method most of the heapification takes place in the lower levels.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Since the height of the heap is $\lfloor \log n\rfloor$ , the number of nodes at height h is $\leq {\frac {2^{\lfloor \log n\rfloor }}{2^{h}}}\leq {\frac {n}{2^{h}}}$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This uses the fact that the given infinite series ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{\infty }i/2^{i}}$ converges.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] where *s*2(*n*) is the sum of all digits of the binary representation of n and *e*2(*n*) is the exponent of 2 in the prime factorization of n.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The average case is more complex to analyze, but it can be shown to asymptotically approach 1.8814 *n* − 2 log2*n* + *O*(1) comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The **Build-Max-Heap** function that follows, converts an array *A* which stores a complete binary tree with *n* nodes to a max-heap by repeatedly using **Max-Heapify** (down-heapify for a max-heap) in a bottom-up manner.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The array elements indexed by *floor*(*n*/2) + 1, *floor*(*n*/2) + 2, ..., *n* are all leaves for the tree (assuming that indices start at 1)—thus each is a one-element heap, and does not need to be down-heapified.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] **Build-Max-Heap** runs **Max-Heapify** on each of the remaining tree nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Heaps are commonly implemented with an array.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Any binary tree can be stored in an array, but because a binary heap is always a complete binary tree, it can be stored compactly.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] No space is required for pointers; instead, the parent and children of each node can be found by arithmetic on array indices.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] These properties make this heap implementation a simple example of an implicit data structure or Ahnentafel list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Details depend on the root position, which in turn may depend on constraints of a programming language used for implementation, or programmer preference.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Specifically, sometimes the root is placed at index 1, in order to simplify arithmetic.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Let *n* be the number of elements in the heap and *i* be an arbitrary valid index of the array storing the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This implementation is used in the heapsort algorithm which reuses the space allocated to the input array to store the heap (i.e. the algorithm is done in-place).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This implementation is also useful as a Priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] When a dynamic array is used, insertion of an unbounded number of items is possible.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The `upheap` or `downheap` operations can then be stated in terms of an array as follows: suppose that the heap property holds for the indices *b*, *b*+1, ..., *e*.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The sift-down function extends the heap property to *b*−1, *b*, *b*+1, ..., *e*.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Only index *i* = *b*−1 can violate the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Let *j* be the index of the largest child of *a*[*i*] (for a max-heap, or the smallest child for a min-heap) within the range *b*, ..., *e*.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] (If no such index exists because 2*i* > *e* then the heap property holds for the newly extended range and nothing needs to be done.) By swapping the values *a*[*i*] and *a*[*j*] the heap property for position *i* is established.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] At this point, the only problem is that the heap property might not hold for index *j*.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The sift-down function is applied tail-recursively to index *j* until the heap property is established for all elements.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] In each step it only needs two comparisons and one swap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The index value where it is working doubles in each iteration, so that at most log2 *e* steps are required.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] For big heaps and using virtual memory, storing elements in an array according to the above scheme is inefficient: (almost) every level is in a different page.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] B-heaps are binary heaps that keep subtrees in a single page, reducing the number of pages accessed by up to a factor of ten.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The operation of merging two binary heaps takes Θ(*n*) for equal-sized heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The best you can do is (in case of array implementation) simply concatenating the two heap arrays and build a heap of the result.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] A heap on *n* elements can be merged with a heap on *k* elements using O(log *n* log *k*) key comparisons, or, in case of a pointer-based implementation, in O(log *n* log *k*) time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] An algorithm for splitting a heap on *n* elements into two heaps on *k* and *n-k* elements, respectively, based on a new view of heaps as an ordered collections of subheaps was presented in.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The algorithm requires O(log *n* * log *n*) comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The view also presents a new and conceptually simple algorithm for merging heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] When merging is a common task, a different heap implementation is recommended, such as binomial heaps, which can be merged in O(log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Additionally, a binary heap can be implemented with a traditional binary tree data structure, but there is an issue with finding the adjacent element on the last level on the binary heap when adding an element.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This element can be determined algorithmically or by adding extra data to the nodes, called "threading" the tree—instead of merely storing references to the children, we store the inorder successor of the node as well.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] It is possible to modify the heap structure to make the extraction of both the smallest and largest element possible in O $(\log n)$ time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] To do this, the rows alternate between min heap and max-heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The algorithms are roughly the same, but, in each step, one must consider the alternating rows with alternating comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The performance is roughly the same as a normal single direction heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This idea can be generalized to a min-max-median heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] In an array-based heap, the children and parent of a node can be located via simple arithmetic on the node's index.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This section derives the relevant equations for heaps with their root at index 0, with additional notes on heaps with their root at index 1.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] To avoid confusion, we define the **level** of a node as its distance from the root, such that the root itself occupies level 0.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] For a general node located at index i (beginning from 0), we will first derive the index of its right child, ${\text{right}}=2i+2$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Let node i be located in level L, and note that any level l contains exactly $2^{l}$ nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Furthermore, there are exactly $2^{l+1}-1$ nodes contained in the layers up to and including layer l (think of binary arithmetic; 0111...111 = 1000...000 - 1).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Because the root is stored at 0, the kth node will be stored at index $(k-1)$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Putting these observations together yields the following expression for the **index of the last node in layer l**.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Each of these j nodes must have exactly 2 children, so there must be $2j$ nodes separating i's right child from the end of its layer ( $L+1$ ).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Noting that the left child of any node is always 1 place before its right child, we get ${\text{left}}=2i+1$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] If the root is located at index 1 instead of 0, the last node in each level is instead at index $2^{l+1}-1$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Using this throughout yields ${\text{left}}=2i$ and ${\text{right}}=2i+1$ for heaps with their root at 1.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Now consider the expression $\left\lfloor {\dfrac {i-1}{2}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] If node i is a left child, this gives the result immediately, however, it also gives the correct result if node i is a right child.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] In this case, $(i-2)$ must be even, and hence $(i-1)$ must be odd.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Since the ordering of siblings in a heap is not specified by the heap property, a single node's two children can be freely interchanged unless doing so violates the shape property (compare with treap).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Note, however, that in the common array-based heap, simply swapping the children might also necessitate moving the children's sub-tree nodes to retain the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The binary heap is a special case of the d-ary heap in which d = 2.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] This does not mean that *sorting* can be done in linear time since building a heap is only the first step of the heapsort algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] *make-heap* is the operation of building a heap from a sequence of *n* unsorted elements.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] It can be done in *Θ*(*n*) time whenever *meld* runs in *O*(log *n*) time (where both complexities can be amortized).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Another algorithm achieves *Θ*(*n*) for binary heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/binary-heap] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A **comparison sort** is a type of sorting algorithm that only reads the list elements through a single abstract comparison operation (often a "less than or equal to" operator or a three-way comparison) that determines which of two elements should occur first in the final sorted list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It is possible that both *a* ≤ *b* and *b* ≤ *a* with *a* ≠ *b*; in this case either may come first in the sorted list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In a stable sort, the input order determines the sorted order in this case.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts studied in the literature are "comparison-based".
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Elements *a* and *b* can be swapped or otherwise re-arranged by the algorithm only when the order between these elements has been established based on the outcomes of prior comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is the case when the order between *a* and *b* can be derived via the transitive closure of these prior comparison outcomes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For comparison-based sorts, the decision to execute basic operations other than comparisons is based on the outcome of comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence in a time analysis, the number of executed comparisons is used to determine upper bound estimates for the number of executed basic operations such as swaps or assignments.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A metaphor for thinking about comparison sorts is that someone has a set of unlabelled weights and a balance scale.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Their goal is to line up the weights in order by their weight without any information except that obtained by placing two weights on the scale and seeing which one is heavier (or if they weigh the same).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] There are fundamental limits on the performance of comparison sorts.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A comparison sort must have an average-case lower bound of Ω(*n* log *n*) comparison operations, which is known as linearithmic time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This is a consequence of the limited information available through comparisons alone — or, to put it differently, of the vague algebraic structure of totally ordered sets.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In this sense, mergesort, heapsort, and introsort are asymptotically optimal in terms of the number of comparisons they must perform, although this metric neglects other operations.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Non-comparison sorts (such as the examples discussed below) can achieve O(*n*) performance by using operations other than comparisons, allowing them to sidestep this lower bound (assuming elements are constant-sized).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts may run faster on some lists; many adaptive sorts such as insertion sort run in O(*n*) time on an already-sorted or nearly-sorted list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Ω(*n* log *n*) lower bound applies only to the case in which the input list can be in any possible order.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Despite these limitations, comparison sorts offer the notable practical advantage that control over the comparison function allows sorting of many different datatypes and fine control over how the list is sorted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Comparison sorts generally adapt more easily to complex orders such as the order of floating-point numbers.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Additionally, once a comparison function is written, any comparison sort can be used without modification; non-comparison sorts typically require specialized versions for each datatype.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This flexibility, together with the efficiency of the above comparison sorting algorithms on modern computers, has led to widespread preference for comparison sorts in most practical work.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Some sorting problems admit a strictly faster solution than the Ω(*n* log *n*) bound for comparison sorting by using non-comparison sorts; an example is integer sorting, where all keys are integers.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] When the keys form a small (compared to n) range, counting sort is an example algorithm that runs in linear time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Other integer sorting algorithms, such as radix sort, are not asymptotically faster than comparison sorting, but can be faster in practice.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The problem of sorting pairs of numbers by their sum is not subject to the Ω(*n*² log *n*) bound either (the square resulting from the pairing up); the best known algorithm still takes O(*n*² log *n*) time, but only O(*n*²) comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The number of comparisons that a comparison sort algorithm requires increases in proportion to $n\log(n)$ , where n is the number of elements to sort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Given a list of distinct numbers (we can assume this because this is a worst-case analysis), there are n factorial permutations exactly one of which is the list in sorted order.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The sort algorithm must gain enough information from the comparisons to identify the correct permutation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If the algorithm always completes after at most $f(n)$ steps, it cannot distinguish more than $2^{f(n)}$ cases because the keys are distinct and each comparison has only two possible outcomes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This provides the lower-bound part of the claim.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A more precise bound can be given via Stirling's approximation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An upper bound of the same form, with the same leading term as the bound obtained from Stirling's approximation, follows from the existence of the algorithms that attain this bound in the worst case, like merge sort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The above argument provides an *absolute*, rather than only asymptotic lower bound on the number of comparisons, namely $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n!)\right\rceil$ comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This lower bound is fairly good (it can be approached within a linear tolerance by a simple merge sort), but it is known to be inexact.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, $\left\lceil \log _{2}(13!)\right\rceil =33$ , but the minimal number of comparisons to sort 13 elements has been proved to be 34.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Determining the *exact* number of comparisons needed to sort a given number of entries is a computationally hard problem even for small *n*, and no simple formula for the solution is known.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For some of the few concrete values that have been computed, see OEIS: A036604.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] A similar bound applies to the average number of comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] it is impossible to determine which order the input is in with fewer than log2(*n*!) comparisons on average.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] This can be most easily seen using concepts from information theory.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The Shannon entropy of such a random permutation is log2(*n*!) bits.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Since a comparison can give only two results, the maximum amount of information it provides is 1 bit.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Therefore, after *k* comparisons the remaining entropy of the permutation, given the results of those comparisons, is at least log2(*n*!) − *k* bits on average.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To perform the sort, complete information is needed, so the remaining entropy must be 0.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It follows that *k* must be at least log2(*n*!) on average.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The lower bound derived via information theory is phrased as 'information-theoretic lower bound'.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The information-theoretic lower bound is correct, but may be far from the strongest possible lower bound.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, the information-theoretic lower bound of selection is $\left\lceil \log _{2}(n)\right\rceil$ whereas $n-1$ comparisons are needed by an adversarial argument.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The interplay between information-theoretic lower bound and the true lower bound are much like a real-valued function lower-bounding an integer function.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] However, this is not exactly correct when the average case is considered.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To unearth what happens while analyzing the average case, the key is that what does 'average' refer to?
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] With some knowledge of information theory, the information-theoretic lower bound averages over the set of all permutations as a whole.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] But any computer algorithms (under what are believed currently) must treat each permutation as an individual instance of the problem.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Hence, the average lower bound we're searching for is averaged over all individual cases.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] To search for the lower bound relating to the non-achievability of computers, we adopt the Decision tree model.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Let's rephrase a bit of what our objective is.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the Decision tree model, the lower bound to be shown is the lower bound of the average length of root-to-leaf paths of an $n!$ -leaf binary tree (in which each leaf corresponds to a permutation).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] The minimum average length of a binary tree with a given number of leaves is achieved by a balanced full binary tree, because any other binary tree can have its path length reduced by moving a pair of leaves to a higher position.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] For example, for *n* = 3, the information-theoretic lower bound for the average case is approximately 2.58, while the average lower bound derived via Decision tree model is 8/3, approximately 2.67.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] In the case that multiple items may have the same key, there is no obvious statistical interpretation for the term "average case", so an argument like the above cannot be applied without making specific assumptions about the distribution of keys.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] Can easy compute for real algorithm sorted-list-merging (array are sorted n-blocks with size 1, merge to 1–1 to 2, merge 2–2 to 4...).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] If a list is already close to sorted, according to some measure of sortedness, the number of comparisons required to sort it can be smaller.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An adaptive sort takes advantage of this "presortedness" and runs more quickly on nearly-sorted inputs, often while still maintaining an $O(n\log n)$ worst case time bound.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] An example is adaptive heap sort, a sorting algorithm based on Cartesian trees.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/comparison-sort] It takes time $O(n\log k)$ , where k is the average, over all values x in the sequence, of the number of times the sequence jumps from below x to above x or vice versa.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] In computer science, a **Fibonacci heap** is a data structure for priority queue operations, consisting of a collection of heap-ordered trees.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] It has a better amortized running time than many other priority queue data structures including the binary heap and binomial heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Tarjan developed Fibonacci heaps in 1984 and published them in a scientific journal in 1987.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Fibonacci heaps are named after the Fibonacci numbers, which are used in their running time analysis.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The amortized times of all operations on Fibonacci heaps is constant, except *delete-min*.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Deleting an element (most often used in the special case of deleting the minimum element) works in $O(\log n)$ amortized time, where n is the size of the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This means that starting from an empty data structure, any sequence of *a* insert and *decrease-key* operations and *b* *delete-min* operations would take $O(a+b\log n)$ worst case time, where n is the maximum heap size.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] In a binary or binomial heap, such a sequence of operations would take $O((a+b)\log n)$ time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] A Fibonacci heap is thus better than a binary or binomial heap when b is smaller than a by a non-constant factor.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] It is also possible to merge two Fibonacci heaps in constant amortized time, improving on the logarithmic merge time of a binomial heap, and improving on binary heaps which cannot handle merges efficiently.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Using Fibonacci heaps improves the asymptotic running time of algorithms which utilize priority queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] For example, Dijkstra's algorithm and Prim's algorithm can be made to run in $O(|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] A Fibonacci heap is a collection of trees satisfying the minimum-heap property, that is, the key of a child is always greater than or equal to the key of the parent.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This implies that the minimum key is always at the root of one of the trees.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Compared with binomial heaps, the structure of a Fibonacci heap is more flexible.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The trees do not have a prescribed shape and in the extreme case the heap can have every element in a separate tree.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This flexibility allows some operations to be executed in a lazy manner, postponing the work for later operations.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] For example, merging heaps is done simply by concatenating the two lists of trees, and operation *decrease key* sometimes cuts a node from its parent and forms a new tree.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] However, at some point order needs to be introduced to the heap to achieve the desired running time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] In particular, degrees of nodes (here degree means the number of direct children) are kept quite low: every node has degree at most $\log n$ and the size of a subtree rooted in a node of degree k is at least $F_{k+2}$ , where $F_{i}$ is the i th Fibonacci number.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This is achieved by the rule: at most one child can be cut off each non-root node.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] When a second child is cut, the node itself needs to be cut from its parent and becomes the root of a new tree (see Proof of degree bounds, below).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The number of trees is decreased in the operation *delete-min*, where trees are linked together.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] As a result of a relaxed structure, some operations can take a long time while others are done very quickly.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] For the amortized running time analysis, we use the potential method, in that we pretend that very fast operations take a little bit longer than they actually do.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This additional time is then later combined and subtracted from the actual running time of slow operations.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The amount of time saved for later use is measured at any given moment by a potential function.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The potential $\phi$ of a Fibonacci heap is given by $\phi =t+2m,$ where t is the number of trees in the Fibonacci heap, and m is the number of marked nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] A node is marked if at least one of its children was cut, since this node was made a child of another node (all roots are unmarked).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The amortized time for an operation is given by the sum of the actual time and c times the difference in potential, where *c* is a constant (chosen to match the constant factors in the big O notation for the actual time).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Thus, the root of each tree in a heap has one unit of time stored.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This unit of time can be used later to link this tree with another tree at amortized time 0.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Also, each marked node has two units of time stored.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] One can be used to cut the node from its parent.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] If this happens, the node becomes a root and the second unit of time will remain stored in it as in any other root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] To allow fast deletion and concatenation, the roots of all trees are linked using a circular doubly linked list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The children of each node are also linked using such a list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] For each node, we maintain its number of children and whether the node is marked.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] We maintain a pointer to the root containing the minimum key, allowing $O(1)$ access to the minimum.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This pointer must be updated during the other operations, which adds only a constant time overhead.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The merge operation simply concatenates the root lists of two heaps together and sets the minimum to be the smaller of the two heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This can be done in constant time, and the potential does not change, leading again to constant amortized time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The insertion operation can be considered a special case of the merge operation, with a single node.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The node is simply appended to the root list, increasing the potential by one.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The amortized cost is thus still constant.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The delete-min operation does most of the work in restoring the structure of the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] We therefore decrease the number of roots by successively linking together roots of the same degree.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] When two roots have the same degree, we make the one with the larger key a child of the other, so that the minimum heap property is conserved.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The degree of the smaller root increases by one.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This is repeated until every root has a different degree.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] To find trees of the same degree efficiently, we use an array of length $O(\log n)$ in which we keep a pointer to one root of each degree.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] When a second root is found of the same degree, the two are linked and the array is updated.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The actual running time is $O(\log n+m)$ , where m is the number of roots at the beginning of the second phase.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] In the end, we will have at most $O(\log n)$ roots (because each has a different degree).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Therefore, the difference in the potential from before to after this phase is $O(\log n)-m$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Thus, the amortized running time is $O(\log n+m)+c(O(\log n)-m)$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] By choosing a sufficiently large c such that the terms in m cancel out, this simplifies to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Search the final list of roots to find the minimum, and update the minimum pointer accordingly.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This takes $O(\log n)$ time, because the number of roots has been reduced.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Overall, the amortized time of this operation is $O(\log n)$ , provided that $d=O(\log n)$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The proof of this is given in the following section.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] If decreasing the key of a node x causes it to become smaller than its parent, then it is cut from its parent, becoming a new unmarked root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] If it is also less than the minimum key, then the minimum pointer is updated.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] We then initiate a series of *cascading cuts*, starting with the parent of x .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] As long as the current node is marked, it is cut from its parent and made an unmarked root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This process stops when we reach an unmarked node y .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] In this process we introduce some number, say k , of new trees.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Except possibly x , each of these new trees loses its original mark.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The terminating node y may become marked.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Therefore, the change in the number of marked nodes is between of $-k$ and $-k+2$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The resulting change in potential is $k+2(-k+2)=-k+4$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The actual time required to perform the cutting was $O(k)$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Hence, the amortized time is $O(k)+c(-k+4)$ , which is constant, provided c is sufficiently large.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The amortized performance of a Fibonacci heap depends on the degree (number of children) of any tree root being $O(\log n)$ , where n is the size of the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Here we show that the size of the (sub)tree rooted at any node x of degree d in the heap must have size at least $F_{d+2}$ , where $F_{i}$ is the i th Fibonacci number.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The degree bound follows from this and the fact (easily proved by induction) that $F_{d+2}\geq \varphi ^{d}$ for all integers $d\geq 0$ , where $\varphi =(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2\approx 1.618$ is the golden ratio.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] We then have $n\geq F_{d+2}\geq \varphi ^{d}$ , and taking the log to base $\varphi$ of both sides gives $d\leq \log _{\varphi }n$ as required.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Let x be an arbitrary node in a Fibonacci heap, not necessarily a root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Define $\mathrm {size} (x)$ to be the size of the tree rooted at x (the number of descendants of x , including x itself).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] We prove by induction on the height of x (the length of the longest path from x to a descendant leaf) that $\mathrm {size} (x)\geq F_{d+2}$ , where d is the degree of x .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] We claim that $c_{i}\geq i-2$ for each i .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Just before $y_{i}$ was made a child of x , $y_{1}\dots y_{i-1}$ were already children of x , and so x must have had degree at least $i-1$ at that time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Since trees are combined only when the degrees of their roots are equal, it must have been the case that $y_{i}$ also had degree at least $i-1$ at the time when it became a child of x .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] From that time to the present, $y_{i}$ could have only lost at most one child (as guaranteed by the marking process), and so its current degree $c_{i}$ is at least $i-2$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This gives the desired lower bound on $\mathrm {size} (x)$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] They are not as efficient in practice when compared with theoretically less efficient forms of heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] In their simplest version, they require manipulation of four pointers per node, whereas only two or three pointers per node are needed in other structures, such as the binomial heap, or pairing heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] This results in large memory consumption per node and high constant factors on all operations.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Although the total running time of a sequence of operations starting with an empty structure is bounded by the bounds given above, some (very few) operations in the sequence can take very long to complete (in particular, delete-min has linear running time in the worst case).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] For this reason, Fibonacci heaps and other amortized data structures may not be appropriate for real-time systems.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] It is possible to create a data structure which has the same worst-case performance as the Fibonacci heap has amortized performance.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] One such structure, the Brodal queue, is, in the words of the creator, "quite complicated" and "[not] applicable in practice." Invented in 2012, the strict Fibonacci heap is a simpler (compared to Brodal's) structure with the same worst-case bounds.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Despite being simpler, experiments show that in practice the strict Fibonacci heap performs slower than more complicated Brodal queue and also slower than basic Fibonacci heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] The run-relaxed heaps of Driscoll et al. give good worst-case performance for all Fibonacci heap operations except merge.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/fibonacci-heap] Recent experimental results suggest that the Fibonacci heap is more efficient in practice than most of its later derivatives, including quake heaps, violation heaps, strict Fibonacci heaps, and rank pairing heaps, but less efficient than pairing heaps or array-based heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Although somewhat slower in practice on most machines than a well-implemented quicksort, it has the advantages of very simple implementation and a more favorable worst-case *O*(*n* log *n*) runtime.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Most real-world quicksort variants include an implementation of heapsort as a fallback should they detect that quicksort is becoming degenerate.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Heapsort is an in-place algorithm, but it is not a stable sort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The paper also introduced the binary heap as a useful data structure in its own right.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Floyd published an improved version that could sort an array in-place, continuing his earlier research into the treesort algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The heapsort algorithm can be divided into two phases: heap construction, and heap extraction.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The heap is an implicit data structure which takes no space beyond the array of objects to be sorted; the array is interpreted as a complete binary tree where each array element is a node and each node's parent and child links are defined by simple arithmetic on the array indexes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] where the floor function rounds down to the preceding integer.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] For a more detailed explanation, see Binary heap § Heap implementation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This binary tree is a max-heap when each node is greater than or equal to both of its children.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Equivalently, each node is less than or equal to its parent.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This rule, applied throughout the tree, results in the maximum node being located at the root of the tree.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] In the first phase, a heap is built out of the data (see Binary heap § Building a heap).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] In the second phase, the heap is converted to a sorted array by repeatedly removing the largest element from the heap (the root of the heap), and placing it at the start of the array.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The heap is updated after each removal to maintain the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Once all objects have been removed from the heap, the result is a sorted array.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Heapsort is normally performed in place.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] During the first phase, the array is divided into an unsorted prefix and a heap-ordered suffix (initially empty).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Each step shrinks the prefix and expands the suffix.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] When the prefix is empty, this phase is complete.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] During the second phase, the array is divided into a heap-ordered prefix and a sorted suffix (initially empty).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] When the prefix is empty, the array is sorted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The heapsort algorithm begins by rearranging the array into a binary max-heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The algorithm then repeatedly swaps the root of the heap (the greatest element remaining in the heap) with its last element, which is then declared to be part of the sorted suffix.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Then the heap, which was damaged by replacing the root, is repaired so that the greatest element is again at the root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This repeats until only one value remains in the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Swap the first element of the array (the largest element in the heap) with the final element of the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Decrease the considered range of the heap by one.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Call the `siftDown()` function on the array to move the new first element to its correct place in the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Go back to step (2) until the remaining array is a single element.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The `heapify()` operation is run once, and is *O*(*n*) in performance.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The `siftDown()` function is called n times and requires *O*(log *n*) work each time, due to its traversal starting from the root node.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Therefore, the performance of this algorithm is *O*(*n* + *n* log *n*) = *O*(*n* log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The heart of the algorithm is the `siftDown()` function.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] To establish the max-heap property at the root, up to three nodes must be compared (the root and its two children), and the greatest must be made the root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This is most easily done by finding the greatest child, then comparing that child to the root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] If root is greater than or equal to the greatest child, the heap property holds and likewise, no further action is required.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] If the root is less than the greatest child, exchange the two nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The heap property now holds at the newly promoted node (it is greater than or equal to both of its children, and in fact greater than any descendant), but may be violated between the newly demoted ex-root and its new children.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] To correct this, repeat the `siftDown()` operation on the subtree rooted at the newly demoted ex-root.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The number of iterations in any one `siftdown()` call is bounded by the height of the tree, which is ⌊log2 *n*⌋ = *O*(log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The following is a simple way to implement the algorithm in pseudocode.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Arrays are zero-based and `swap` is used to exchange two elements of the array.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Movement 'down' means from the root towards the leaves, or from lower indices to higher.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Note that during the sort, the largest element is at the root of the heap at `a[0]`, while at the end of the sort, the largest element is in `a[end]`.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The sorting routine uses two subroutines, `heapify` and `siftDown`.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The former is the common in-place heap construction routine, while the latter is a common subroutine for implementing `heapify`.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The `heapify` procedure operates by building small heaps and repeatedly merging them using `siftDown`.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] It starts with the leaves, observing that they are trivial but valid heaps by themselves, and then adds parents.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Starting with element *n*/2 and working backwards, each internal node is made the root of a valid heap by sifting down.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The last step is sifting down the first element, after which the entire array obeys the heap property.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] To see that this takes *O*(*n*) time, count the worst-case number of `siftDown` iterations.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The last half of the array requires zero iterations, the preceding quarter requires at most one iteration, the eighth before that requires at most two iterations, the sixteenth before that requires at most three, and so on.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Looked at a different way, if we assume every `siftDown` call requires the maximum number of iterations, the first half of the array requires one iteration, the first quarter requires one more (total 2), the first eighth requires yet another (total 3), and so on.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This totals *n*/2 + *n*/4 + *n*/8 + ⋯ = n⋅(1/2 + 1/4 + 1/8 + ⋯), where the infinite sum is a well-known geometric series whose sum is 1, thus the product is simply n.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The exact worst-case number of comparisons during the heap-construction phase of heapsort is known to be equal to 2*n* − 2*s*2(*n*) − *e*2(*n*), where *s*2(*n*) is the number of 1 bits in the binary representation of n and *e*2(*n*) is the number of trailing 0 bits.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Although it is convenient to think of the two phases separately, most implementations combine the two, allowing a single instance of `siftDown`to be expanded inline.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Two variables (here, `start` and `end`) keep track of the bounds of the heap area.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The portion of the array before `start` is unsorted, while the portion beginning at `end` is sorted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Heap construction decreases `start` until it is zero, after which heap extraction decreases `end` until it is 1 and the array is entirely sorted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The description above uses Floyd's improved heap-construction algorithm, which operates in *O*(*n*) time and uses the same `siftDown` primitive as the heap-extraction phase.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Although this algorithm, being both faster and simpler to program, is used by all practical heapsort implementations, Williams' original algorithm may be easier to understand, and is needed to implement a more general binary heap priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Rather than merging many small heaps, Williams' algorithm maintains one single heap at the front of the array and repeatedly appends an additional element using a `siftUp` primitive.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Being at the end of the array, the new element is a leaf and has no children to worry about, but may violate the heap property by being greater than its parent.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] In this case, exchange it with its parent and repeat the test until the parent is greater or there is no parent (we have reached the root).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] To understand why this algorithm can take asymptotically more time to build a heap (*O*(*n* log *n*) vs.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] *O*(*n*) worst case), note that in Floyd's algorithm, almost all the calls to `siftDown` operations apply to very *small* heaps.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Half the heaps are height-1 trivial heaps and can be skipped entirely, half of the remainder are height-2, and so on.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Only two calls are on heaps of size *n*/2, and only one `siftDown` operation is done on the full n-element heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The overall average `siftDown` operation takes *O*(1) time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] In contrast, in Williams' algorithm most of the calls to `siftUp` are made on *large* heaps of height *O*(log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Half of the calls are made with a heap size of *n*/2 or more, three-quarters are made with a heap size of *n*/4 or more, and so on.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Because it is dominated by the second heap-extraction phase, the heapsort algorithm itself has *O*(*n* log *n*) time complexity using either version of heapify.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Bottom-up heapsort is a variant that reduces the number of comparisons required by a significant factor.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] While ordinary "top-down" heapsort requires 2*n* log2 *n* + *O*(*n*) comparisons worst-case and on average, the bottom-up variant requires *n* log2*n* + *O*(1) comparisons on average, and 1.5*n* log2*n* + *O*(*n*) in the worst case.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] If comparisons are cheap (e.g. integer keys) then the difference is unimportant, as top-down heapsort compares values that have already been loaded from memory.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] If, however, comparisons require a function call or other complex logic, then bottom-up heapsort is advantageous.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This is accomplished by using a more elaborate `siftDown` procedure.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The change improves the linear-time heap-building phase slightly, but is more significant in the second phase.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Like top-down heapsort, each iteration of the second phase extracts the top of the heap, `a[0]`, and fills the gap it leaves with `a[end]`, then sifts this latter element down the heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] But this element came from the lowest level of the heap, meaning it is one of the smallest elements in the heap, so the sift-down will likely take many steps to move it back down.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] In top-down heapsort, each step of `siftDown` requires two comparisons, to find the minimum of three elements: the new node and its two children.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This places the root in the same location as top-down `siftDown`, but fewer comparisons are required to find that location.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] A naïve implementation of this conceptual algorithm would cause some redundant data copying, as the sift-up portion undoes part of the sifting down.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] A practical implementation searches downward for a leaf where −∞ *would* be placed, then upward for where the root *should* be placed.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Finally, the upward traversal continues to the root's starting position, performing no more comparisons but exchanging nodes to complete the necessary rearrangement.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] This optimized form performs the same number of exchanges as top-down `siftDown`.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Because it goes all the way to the bottom and then comes back up, it is called **heapsort with bounce** by some authors.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Bottom-up heapsort was announced as beating quicksort (with median-of-three pivot selection) on arrays of size ≥16000.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] A 2008 re-evaluation of this algorithm showed it to be no faster than top-down heapsort for integer keys, presumably because modern branch prediction nullifies the cost of the predictable comparisons that bottom-up heapsort manages to avoid.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] A further refinement does a binary search in the upward search, and sorts in a worst case of (*n*+1)(log2(*n*+1) + log2 log2(*n*+1) + 1.82) + *O*(log2*n*) comparisons, approaching the information-theoretic lower bound of *n* log2*n* − 1.4427*n* comparisons.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] A variant that uses two extra bits per internal node (*n*−1 bits total for an *n*-element heap) to cache information about which child is greater (two bits are required to store three cases: left, right, and unknown) uses less than *n* log2*n* + 1.1*n* compares.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Heapsort primarily competes with quicksort, another very efficient general purpose in-place unstable comparison-based sort algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Heapsort's primary advantages are its simple, non-recursive code, minimal auxiliary storage requirement, and reliably good performance: its best and worst cases are within a small constant factor of each other, and of the theoretical lower bound on comparison sorts.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] While it cannot do better than *O*(*n* log *n*) for pre-sorted inputs, it does not suffer from quicksort's *O*(*n*2) worst case, either.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Real-world quicksort implementations use a variety of heuristics to avoid the worst case, but that makes their implementation far more complex, and implementations such as introsort and pattern-defeating quicksort use heapsort as a last-resort fallback if they detect degenerate behaviour.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Thus, their worst-case performance is slightly worse than if heapsort had been used from the beginning.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Heapsort's primary disadvantages are its poor locality of reference and its inherently serial nature; the accesses to the implicit tree are widely scattered and mostly random, and there is no straightforward way to convert it to a parallel algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The worst-case performance guarantees make heapsort popular in real-time computing, and systems concerned with maliciously chosen inputs such as the Linux kernel.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The combination of small implementation and dependably "good enough" performance make it popular in embedded systems, and generally any application where sorting is not a performance bottleneck.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] E.g. heapsort is ideal for sorting a list of filenames for display, but a database management system would probably want a more aggressively optimized sorting algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] A well-implemented quicksort is usually 2–3 times faster than heapsort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Although quicksort requires fewer comparisons, this is a minor factor.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] (Results claiming twice as many comparisons are measuring the top-down version; see § Bottom-up heapsort.) The main advantage of quicksort is its much better locality of reference: partitioning is a linear scan with good spatial locality, and the recursive subdivision has good temporal locality.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] With additional effort, quicksort can also be implemented in mostly branch-free code, and multiple CPUs can be used to sort subpartitions in parallel.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] Thus, quicksort is preferred when the additional performance justifies the implementation effort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The other major *O*(*n* log *n*) sorting algorithm is merge sort, but that rarely competes directly with heapsort because it is not in-place.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The examples sort the values { 6, 5, 3, 1, 8, 7, 2, 4 } in increasing order using both heap-construction algorithms.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] The elements being compared are shown in a **bold** font.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/heapsort] There are typically two when sifting up, and three when sifting down, although there may be fewer when the top or bottom of the tree is reached.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In computer science, an **in-place algorithm** is an algorithm that operates directly on the input data structure without requiring extra space proportional to the input size.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In other words, it modifies the input in place, without creating a separate copy of the data structure.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] An algorithm which is not in-place is sometimes called **not-in-place** or **out-of-place**.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In-place can have slightly different meanings.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In its strictest form, the algorithm can only have a constant amount of extra space, counting everything including function calls and pointers.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, this form is very limited as simply having an index to a length *n* array requires *O*(log *n*) bits.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] More broadly, in-place means that the algorithm does not use extra space for manipulating the input but may require a small though non-constant extra space for its operation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Usually, this space is *O*(log *n*), though sometimes anything in *o*(*n*) is allowed.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Note that space complexity also has varied choices in whether or not to count the index lengths as part of the space used.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Often, the space complexity is given in terms of the number of indices or pointers needed, ignoring their length.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In this article, we refer to total space complexity (DSPACE), counting pointer lengths.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Therefore, the space requirements here have an extra log *n* factor compared to an analysis that ignores the lengths of indices and pointers.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] An algorithm may or may not count the output as part of its space usage.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Since in-place algorithms usually overwrite their input with output, no additional space is needed.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] When writing the output to write-only memory or a stream, it may be more appropriate to only consider the working space of the algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In theoretical applications such as log-space reductions, it is more typical to always ignore output space (in these cases it is more essential that the output is *write-only*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Given an array `a` of *n* items, suppose we want an array that holds the same elements in reversed order and to dispose of the original.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] One seemingly simple way to do this is to create a new array of equal size, fill it with copies from `a` in the appropriate order and then delete `a`.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Unfortunately, this requires *O*(*n*) extra space for having the arrays `a` and `b` available simultaneously.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Also, allocation and deallocation are often slow operations.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Since we no longer need `a`, we can instead overwrite it with its own reversal using this in-place algorithm which will only need constant number (2) of integers for the auxiliary variables `i` and `tmp`, no matter how large the array is.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] As another example, many sorting algorithms rearrange arrays into sorted order in-place, including: bubble sort, comb sort, selection sort, insertion sort, heapsort, and Shell sort.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] These algorithms require only a few pointers, so their space complexity is *O*(log *n*).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Quicksort operates in-place on the data to be sorted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, quicksort requires *O*(log *n*) stack space pointers to keep track of the subarrays in its divide and conquer strategy.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Consequently, quicksort needs *O*(log2 *n*) additional space.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Although this non-constant space technically takes quicksort out of the in-place category, quicksort and other algorithms needing only *O*(log *n*) additional pointers are usually considered in-place algorithms.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Most selection algorithms are also in-place, although some considerably rearrange the input array in the process of finding the final, constant-sized result.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Some text manipulation algorithms such as trim and reverse may be done in-place.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In computational complexity theory, the strict definition of in-place algorithms includes all algorithms with *O*(1) space complexity, the class **DSPACE**(1).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This class is very limited; it equals the regular languages.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In fact, it does not even include any of the examples listed above.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Algorithms are usually considered in L, the class of problems requiring *O*(log *n*) additional space, to be in-place.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This class is more in line with the practical definition, as it allows numbers of size *n* as pointers or indices.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This expanded definition still excludes quicksort, however, because of its recursive calls.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] This in turn yields in-place algorithms for problems such as determining if a graph is bipartite or testing whether two graphs have the same number of connected components.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] In many cases, the space requirements of an algorithm can be drastically cut by using a randomized algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] For example, if one wishes to know if two vertices in a graph of *n* vertices are in the same connected component of the graph, there is no known simple, deterministic, in-place algorithm to determine this.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, if we simply start at one vertex and perform a random walk of about 20*n*3 steps, the chance that we will stumble across the other vertex provided that it is in the same component is very high.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Similarly, there are simple randomized in-place algorithms for primality testing such as the Miller–Rabin primality test, and there are also simple in-place randomized factoring algorithms such as Pollard's rho algorithm.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Functional programming languages often discourage or do not support explicit in-place algorithms that overwrite data, since this is a type of side effect; instead, they only allow new data to be constructed.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] However, good functional language compilers will often recognize when an object very similar to an existing one is created and then the old one is thrown away, and will optimize this into a simple mutation "under the hood".
[src:heapsort-algorithm/in-place-algorithm] Note that it is possible in principle to carefully construct in-place algorithms that do not modify data (unless the data is no longer being used), but this is rarely done in practice.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:heapsort-algorithm/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
